I recently completed a hands-on cybersecurity lab focused on building a basic SOC (Security Operations Center) monitoring environment using Sysmon and Splunk Enterprise.

🎯 Objective
To generate endpoint telemetry using Sysmon on Windows 11 and successfully ingest and analyze it in Splunk for security monitoring and attack visibility.

🧪 Tools Used

Windows 11 (Host Machine)
Sysmon (System Monitor by Microsoft Sysinternals)
Splunk Enterprise
Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Windows
Kali Linux (planned for attack simulation)

⚙️ Steps Performed

1. Installed and configured Sysmon on Windows

Sysmon was installed and configured to generate detailed system activity logs.

Command used:

.\Sysmon64.exe -accepteula -i sysmonconfig-export.xml
2. Verified Sysmon logging in Windows

Confirmed Sysmon was generating events:

Get-WinEvent -LogName "Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational" -MaxEvents 5
3. Configured Splunk to ingest Windows Event Logs

Enabled Windows Event Log collection in Splunk and initially monitored:

Security logs
System logs
Application logs

4. Installed Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Windows

Installed the Splunk TA to enable proper parsing and field extraction of Windows event logs including Sysmon.

5. Verified Sysmon ingestion in Splunk

Confirmed Sysmon logs were being ingested successfully:

index=main source="WinEventLog:Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational"
6. Validated Event types (Security visibility achieved)

Process creation events:

index=main source="WinEventLog:Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational" EventCode=1
Network connection events:

index=main source="WinEventLog:Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational" EventCode=3 | head 10
🔍 Outcome

Successfully built endpoint visibility using Sysmon
Ingested and analyzed logs in Splunk Enterprise
Confirmed both process creation and network connection telemetry
Prepared environment for attack simulation and SOC detection use cases

Although, I faced a major challenge because splunk wasn’t reading logs from Sysmon, it troubled me for sometime but in the end I was able to fix it by modyfing the inputs.conf file in the splunk directory. I really enjoyed the challenges I faced in setting up everything.

Here is the modification in inputs.conf

[WinEventLog://Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational]
disabled = 0
index = main
renderXml = true
